quran[12]{c,v,t,f}:
  19,88,"They claim: "
  19,89,"Surely you have made a monstrous statement."
  19,90,"It is such a monstrosity that heavens might well-nigh burst forth at it, the earth might be cleaved, and the mountains fall"
  20,70,"Eventually the magicians were impelled to fall down prostrate{1} and said: ",footnotes:1:When they saw the power of the staff of Moses (peace be upon him), they involuntarily fell prostrate as if someone had made them do so, because they were convinced that it was a miracle and not a feat of magic.
  20,71,"Pharaoh said: ",footnotes:1:That is, right hand and left foot or vice versa.
  20,72,"The magicians answered: ",footnotes:1:It may also be interpreted like this: It cannot be that we should prefer you to these plain signs which have come before us and to that Being Who has created us.
  21,46,"Were only the slightest whiff from your Lord's punishment to touch them,{1} they would cry out: ",footnotes:1:That is, the same scourge which they are demanding to be hastened and of which they are making fun.
  21,47,"We shall set up just scales on the Day of Resurrection so that none will be wronged in the least. (We shall bring forth the acts of everyone), even if it be the weight of a grain of mustard seed. We shall suffice as Reckoners.{1}",footnotes:1:See also (verses 8-9 and E.Ns 8-9 of Surah Al-Aaraf). It is difficult for us to understand the exact nature of the balance. Anyhow, it is clear that the balance will weigh accurately all the human moral deeds instead of material things, and will help judge whether a man is virtuous or wicked and how much. The Quran has used this word to make mankind understand that every deed, good or bad, will be weighed and judged according to merit.
  21,48,"Surely{1} We had granted to Moses and Aaron the Criterion{2} (between right and wrong), and Light and Admonition for the good of the God-fearing,{3}",footnotes:1:From here begin the stories of the Prophets. If we consider these stories in the context in which they occur, it becomes clear that these have been related to impress the following themes.,footnotes:2:(1) All the former Prophets were human beings. Therefore there is nothing strange or unusual that a human being like Muhammad (peace be upon him) has been sent as a Messenger.,footnotes:3:(2) The mission and teachings of this Prophet are the same as of those who were sent before him.
  22,22,"Whenever they try, in their anguish, to escape from Hell, they will be driven back into it, (and shall be told): "
  22,23,"(On the other hand), Allah will cause those who believed and acted righteously to enter the Gardens beneath which rivers flow. They shall be decked in them with bracelets of gold and pearls{1} and their raiment shall be of silk.",footnotes:1:This is to show that they will be honored like the kings and chiefs who used to wear ornaments of gold and jewelry in the period the Quran was revealed.
  22,24,"They were guided (to accept) the pure word;{1} they were guided to the Way of the Praiseworthy (Lord).{2}",footnotes:1:“Purest of the speeches”: though it may imply every pure thing, here it refers to the basic articles of the faith.,footnotes:2:As already stated in the introduction, the portion of the Surah, which was revealed at Makkah, comes to an end here. Though its style is clearly that of the Makki Surahs and there is nothing to indicate that any part (or the whole) of it was revealed at Al-Madinah, yet the words, “these are the two parties”, have given rise to the misunderstanding that this verse was revealed at Al-Madinah. Some commentators are of the opinion that the two parties referred to were the parties who met in the Battle of Badr, but there is nothing in the context to support this opinion. On the other hand, from the context in which these words occur, it becomes obvious that the two parties referred to were the believers and the disbelievers. For the conflict between belief and disbelief has always been going on ever since the creation of man and will go on upto the Day of Resurrection.
